{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17472339","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17472339"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:56:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:56:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1253"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1253","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1253"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.21,0.03,0.02,0.01,0.73]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1253"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106631"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1253","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1253"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1253"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89109"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"3021"},{"type":"tags","id":"4957"},{"type":"tags","id":"4971"},{"type":"tags","id":"11632"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"458"},{"type":"contributions","id":"519"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23606"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28681"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29696"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42261"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44046"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106631","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106631"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 14-year-old girl presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of fatigue and easy bruising. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She performs well at school, has many friends and a supportive family. Two years ago, she had a negative experience in hospital when several attempts at intravenous cannulation failed and a nasogastric tube was required for fluid administration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well, with vital signs within normal limits. When blood tests are suggested, she becomes visibly distressed, starts sweating, and hides behind her parent. She firmly refuses venepuncture despite counselling about its importance and offers of topical local anaesthetic. Multiple attempts at persuasion are unsuccessful and she becomes tearful. Her parent reports that she has been avoiding medical appointments and becomes distressed when watching medical scenes on television.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Other specified trauma and stressor-related disorder","Illness anxiety disorder","Panic disorder","Generalised anxiety disorder","Specific phobia"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features characteristic of needle phobia, a type of \u003Cstrong\u003Especific phobia\u003C/strong\u003E. The key diagnostic features include immediate anxiety response, expressed fear out of proportion to actual risk, physical signs of anxiety (sweating), and marked avoidance behaviour (hiding behind parent) when confronted with needles. Importantly, her anxiety is specifically triggered by needles and does not significantly impair other aspects of her life, as evidenced by her good academic performance and social relationships.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOther specified trauma and stressor-related disorder\u003C/strong\u003E might be considered given her previous traumatic hospital experience and distress by medical scenes on television. However, her presentation does not meet the diagnostic criteria for this condition. Her symptoms are better explained by a specific phobia, as they are focused specifically on needles and demonstrate the classic pattern of immediate fear response and avoidance behaviour characteristic of phobic disorders.  Avoiding the medical scenes on television would be part of actively avoiding seeing the specific phobia of needles. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIllness anxiety disorder\u003C/strong\u003E involves preoccupation with having or acquiring a serious illness. In this case, the patient\u0027s anxiety is specifically directed towards needles rather than concerns about her health status.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPanic disorder\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by recurrent unexpected panic attacks followed by persistent concern about additional attacks or maladaptive behavioural changes. This patient\u0027s anxiety is specifically triggered by needles rather than being unexpected or spontaneous.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGeneralised anxiety disorder\u003C/strong\u003E involves excessive anxiety about multiple life domains that is difficult to control. This patient\u0027s anxiety is specific to needles and does not generalise to other aspects of her life.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Specific phobia is characterised by immediate, excessive fear of a specific object or situation with associated avoidance behaviour.","The key diagnostic criteria for specific phobia include fear that is persistent, unreasonable, and disproportionate to the actual danger.","Avoidance of medical-related media and appointments can be manifestations of specific phobia rather than trauma-related disorders when the fear is focused on a specific trigger."],"references":["LeBeau RT, Glenn D, Liao B, et al. Specific phobia: a review of DSM-IV specific phobia and preliminary recommendations for DSM-V. Depress Anxiety 2010; 27:148.","Substance Abuse and Mental Health Services Administration. Impact of the DSM-IV to DSM-5 Changes on the National Survey on Drug Use and Health [Internet]. Rockville (MD): Substance Abuse and Mental Health Services Administration (US); 2016 Jun. Table 3.11, DSM-IV to DSM-5 Specific Phobia Comparison. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK519704/table/ch3.t11/ (accessed April 7, 2023)"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89109"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1253"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89109","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89109"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-21T00:05:12+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-21T00:05:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1253"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106631"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tag